document_title: Password Reset Process for Active Directory Users
chunk_text: This document outlines the standard operating procedure for help desk technicians to reset user passwords within Active Directory. This process ensures security compliance and efficient resolution of user access issues.

document_title: Password Reset Process for Active Directory Users
chunk_text:
Before You Begin: Ensure you have appropriate administrative privileges in Active Directory Users and Computers (ADUC) and have verified the user's identity according to company policy.

Step-by-Step Instructions:

Open Active Directory Users and Computers (ADUC):: On your administrative workstation, open Server Manager, then navigate to Tools > Active Directory Users and Computers.

Locate the User Account:: In the ADUC console, browse to the Organizational Unit (OU) where the user's account is located. You can also use the "Find" feature (Ctrl+F) to search for the user by name.

Reset Password:: Right-click on the user account, select "Reset Password...".

document_title: Password Reset Process for Active Directory Users
chunk_text:
Enter New Password:: In the "Reset Password" dialog box, enter a new, strong password in both the "New password" and "Confirm password" fields. Ensure the password meets complexity requirements.

Set User Options:: Typically, you should check "User must change password at next logon" to enforce a new password creation by the user. Uncheck "Account is locked out" if it is checked.

Confirm Reset:: Click "OK" to complete the password reset. Inform the user of their temporary password and instruct them to change it immediately upon logging in.

document_title: Password Reset Process for Active Directory Users
chunk_text: Important Note: Never share temporary passwords via unencrypted channels (e.g., unencrypted email or chat). Always communicate them securely, preferably verbally or through a secure, one-time password system.

document_title: Password Reset Process for Active Directory Users
chunk_text:
For experienced technicians, a password can also be reset using PowerShell:

Code Example:
Set-ADUser -Identity "username" -NewPassword (Read-Host -AsSecureString "Enter new password") -ChangePasswordAtLogon $true

Replace"username"with the actual user's SAMAccountName.

document_title: Password Reset Process for Active Directory Users
chunk_text: Success Indicators: The password reset is successful when:The user is able to log in with the new temporary password.The user is prompted to change their password upon first login (if "User must change password at next logon" was checked).The user confirms successful access to their resources.

This article provides step-by-step instructions to diagnose and resolve common email client connection problems, including issues with sending, receiving, or accessing email through desktop applications like Microsoft Outlook or Mozilla Thunderbird, and web-based email services.

: Email client displays "Disconnected" or "Needs Password" message.

: Unable to send or receive emails.

: Error messages like "Server not found," "Connection timed out," or "Authentication failed."

: Webmail access issues (e.g., unable to log in, page not loading).

: Emails stuck in outbox.

Email connection issues can stem from various sources, including incorrect account settings, network connectivity problems, firewall/antivirus interference, or server-side outages. This guide will help you systematically check for these common causes.

Before You Begin: Ensure your computer is connected to the internet and try accessing a website (e.g., google.com) to confirm basic network connectivity. Step-by-Step Instructions: Check Internet Connection:: Verify your device has an active internet connection. Try opening a web browser and navigating to a known website like https://www.google.com. If you cannot access websites, troubleshoot your network connection first. Verify Email Account Settings:: Incorrect server settings (IMAP/POP3, SMTP), port numbers, or encryption methods are common culprits. Refer to your email provider's documentation for the correct settings. For corporate email, contact your IT department.

Check Password:: Confirm you are using the correct password. If you recently changed your email password, update it in your email client settings. Try logging into your webmail directly to rule out a password issue.

Disable Firewall/Antivirus Temporarily:: Security software can sometimes block email client connections. Temporarily disable your firewall or antivirus software and try connecting. If this resolves the issue, configure your security software to allow your email client.

Restart Email Client and Computer:: A simple restart can often resolve temporary glitches. Close your email client completely and reopen it. If the issue persists, restart your computer.

Repair/Recreate Email Profile (Outlook Specific):: For Microsoft Outlook, a corrupted mail profile can cause connection issues. You can try repairing your existing profile or creating a new one via the Mail Setup (Outlook) in Control Panel.

Important Note: Temporarily disabling security software should only be done for testing purposes. Re-enable it immediately after testing to protect your system.

You can use thepingcommand to test connectivity to your email server:

Code Example:
ping mail.example.com
          telnet mail.example.com 993

Replacemail.example.comwith your actual email server address and993with the appropriate port (e.g., 587 for SMTP, 993 for IMAPS, 995 for POP3S).

Issue: "Authentication Failed"; Possible Cause: Incorrect username/password or server settings.; Solution: Verify credentials and server settings. Enable 2FA app password if applicable.
Issue: "Connection Timed Out"; Possible Cause: Network blockage, incorrect port, or server offline.; Solution: Check firewall, verify port numbers, ping server address.
Issue: Emails stuck in Outbox; Possible Cause: SMTP server issue, large attachment, or offline mode.; Solution: Verify SMTP settings, reduce attachment size, ensure client is online.
